            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born and raised in the fog-dusted avenues of San Francisco\u2019s Richmond District, David Leung is the son of pragmatic Hong Kong immigrants who equated success with a career in engineering or medicine. David, dutiful and bright, followed this path through Lowell High School and into his first years at UC Berkeley, initially declared as a pre-med major. His true passion, however, was found not in sterile labs but in the chaotic, collaborative world of student theater, where he discovered a gift for organization and stage management.\n\nThis became his turning point. Defying his parents\u2019 expectations, he switched his focus, culminating in a Master's degree in Arts Administration from San Francisco State University. The decision caused a quiet rift with his father, one that took years to mend. David\u2019s early career was a grind in the city\u2019s vibrant but underfunded arts scene, writing grants for a small dance troupe and managing fundraising events for a theater company in the Mission. He learned he had a unique talent: translating artistic passion into compelling narratives for potential donors.\n\nHis career pivoted when he was recruited by a major scientific museum in Golden Gate Park. He found he could apply the same skills to a different kind of mission, securing funding for research and educational outreach. Now, as Director of Institutional Advancement, David masterfully bridges two worlds\u2014the analytical minds of scientists and the philanthropic hearts of the city\u2019s elite.\n\nDavid lives in a meticulously kept apartment in Cole Valley, a short MUNI ride from his office. His daily routine is structured: a morning commute listening to a history podcast, a day of strategic meetings and donor lunches, and quiet evenings often spent reading. Though single after a long-term relationship ended in his forties, his life is rich with connections forged over decades\u2014a close-knit circle of friends from his theater days and respected colleagues. His ultimate aspiration is to secure a landmark endowment for the museum, a legacy that will support scientific discovery for generations. He finds a deep, satisfying irony in having built his success not by abandoning his path, but by proving its unexpected power."
